WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.525 --> 00:00:57.400
In 2019, an eight-year-old cricketer was brought to a district hospital in Tamil Nadu, after falling awkwardly on his outstretched hand. X-rays were taken, and a fracture was confirmed. But the break was not through the main shaft of the bone. It passed through a thin strip of cartilage near the bone's end. That cartilage is nearly invisible on early X-rays, and very easy to miss. Weeks later, his right arm stopped growing. That thin strip of cartilage is called the epiphyseal plate. It sits between the rounded end of the bone and the main shaft. It is where active cartilage cells lay down new bone tissue, allowing the bone to lengthen throughout childhood. When an injury damages the epiphyseal plate and the diagnosis is missed, growth stops on that side. The result is a permanent difference in limb length. This module is about understanding bones and joints deeply enough that you will never make that kind of mistake.

2
00:00:57.400 --> 00:02:24.800
Think about what a freshly cut femur, the thigh bone, actually looks like. It is not the chalk-white structure from school diagrams. It has a slight yellow tinge and feels moist when freshly sectioned. That is because bone is a living organ, not a dead mineral store. Cut a long bone lengthwise and you find four distinct layers. The first is the periosteum, a tough fibrous sleeve covering the bone's outer surface. It has two parts. The outer layer is fibrous and anchors tendons and ligaments. The inner layer is osteogenic, meaning bone-forming, and its cells are responsible for repairing fractures. The periosteum is densely supplied with nerve fibers. This is why breaking a bone is so intensely painful. Next comes compact bone, also called cortical bone, the hard dense outer shell. Its internal structure forms concentric rings called osteons, also known as Haversian systems, giving bone its remarkable strength and rigidity. Beneath that is spongy bone, also called cancellous or trabecular bone. It forms a honeycomb of bony struts called trabeculae, filled with bone marrow. Red marrow produces blood cells. Yellow marrow is mostly fat. This open architecture reduces weight while maintaining strength. Finally, the endosteum lines the inner surface of compact bone and the spaces within spongy bone. It contains two key cell types: osteoblasts, which form new bone, and osteoclasts, which break bone down.

3
00:02:24.800 --> 00:03:44.200
Bones are classified by shape, because shape reflects mechanical function. Long bones, like the femur and humerus, are built for leverage and movement. Short bones, like the carpals of the wrist and tarsals of the ankle, provide compact strength. Flat bones, like the skull vault and sternum, protect organs and offer broad muscle attachment surfaces. Irregular bones, like the vertebrae and hip bone, have complex shapes for complex functions. Pneumatic bones, like the maxilla and frontal bone, contain air sinuses that reduce skull weight. Sesamoid bones are embedded within tendons. The name comes from the Arabic word simsim, meaning sesame seed. These bones develop where tendons cross joints under high pressure. The patella, the kneecap, is the largest sesamoid. It sits within the quadriceps tendon. This position shifts that tendon away from the knee joint axis, increasing the muscle's mechanical advantage. The pisiform, a small wrist bone, is a sesamoid in the flexor carpi ulnaris tendon. Two sesamoids beneath the first metatarsal head protect the flexor hallucis longus tendon. Clinically, sesamoids can fracture or develop avascular necrosis. The patella is the classic example. A patellar fracture disrupts the quadriceps mechanism, and the patient cannot extend the knee against gravity.

4
00:03:44.200 --> 00:05:17.500
Bone has a dedicated blood supply that supports growth, repair, and ongoing metabolic activity. A long bone receives blood from four distinct sources. First, the nutrient artery is the main supply. It enters the shaft, called the diaphysis, through a small opening called the nutrient foramen. Inside, it branches upward and downward, supplying the marrow and the inner two-thirds of cortical bone. Next, the metaphyseal vessels are multiple small arteries entering the flared ends of the bone, the metaphyses. These supply the growth plate region. Then come the epiphyseal vessels, which enter the rounded bone ends near the articular margin. Before the growth plate fuses, these vessels are completely separate from the metaphyseal vessels. This matters because the epiphysis relies on its own isolated blood supply. Any disruption can cut it off entirely, leading to avascular necrosis. Perthes disease, avascular necrosis of the femoral head seen in children, is a classic example of this vulnerability. Finally, the periosteal vessels supply the outer one-third of cortical bone. Bone also has a nerve supply worth understanding. The periosteum, the fibrous outer covering of bone, is richly supplied with pain fibres. This is why fractures and periostitis cause such intense, localized pain. The bone tissue itself carries vasomotor fibres that regulate blood flow. The endosteum and marrow also have sensory fibres, which explains the deep aching pain patients experience with bone metastases.

5
00:05:17.500 --> 00:06:39.225
Ossification is the process of bone formation. The word comes from Latin, where os means bone and facere means to make. There are two distinct mechanisms, and which one is used depends on the type of bone being formed. The first is intramembranous ossification. Here, bone forms directly from a sheet of embryonic connective tissue called mesenchyme. Mesenchymal cells differentiate into osteoblasts, the cells that secrete bone matrix, without first forming a cartilage model. The flat bones of the skull vault form this way, including the frontal, parietal, occipital, and temporal bones. So do the clavicle and mandible. This matters clinically because these bones are not yet fused at birth. The fontanelles, the soft spots on a newborn's skull, close gradually over the first eighteen months of life. The second mechanism is endochondral ossification. Here, bone forms within a pre-existing cartilage model, which is then gradually replaced by bone tissue. All long bones form this way, as do the vertebrae, pelvis, ribs, and most of the skull base. In endochondral ossification, the primary ossification centre appears in the diaphysis, the shaft of the bone, during fetal life. By birth, the diaphysis is already ossified. Radiologists use the presence or absence of ossification centres to estimate gestational age on fetal ultrasound.

6
00:06:39.225 --> 00:08:02.925
After birth, secondary ossification centres appear in the epiphyses, the rounded ends of each bone. Their timing varies between bones. You will study exact fusion ages during the Forensic Medicine posting. Between each epiphysis and the diaphysis, the central shaft, lies a thin disc of hyaline cartilage. This disc is the epiphyseal plate, also called the growth plate or physis. It is the engine of longitudinal bone growth. New cartilage cells form here, and bone steadily replaces them on the diaphyseal side, lengthening the bone. At puberty, rising oestrogen and testosterone cause the remaining cartilage to be replaced by bone. This is called epiphyseal fusion. A faint epiphyseal line on X-ray is all that remains. Once fused, the bone can no longer increase in length. Fusion timing matters in forensic age estimation. The medial clavicle fuses last, at around twenty-five years. It is the most reliable single landmark for skeletal maturity. The mnemonic SCIMITAR captures this: Sternal end of Clavicle Is Mostly The Absolute Record. The iliac crest fuses between seventeen and twenty-two years. One cross-subject connection: bone matrix is built largely from type one collagen. Vitamin C is required for collagen hydroxylation, which is exactly why scurvy causes bone fragility.

7
00:08:02.925 --> 00:09:30.975
Cartilage is a specialised connective tissue with three properties bone lacks. It is avascular, with no blood vessels. It is aneural, with no nerves. And it is highly resilient, flexing under compression without breaking. Because cartilage is avascular, nutrients cannot arrive through the bloodstream. They diffuse slowly through the matrix, from the perichondrium, the fibrous outer covering, or from synovial fluid in joint cartilage. This is why cartilage heals so poorly; there are no vessels to bring repair cells. There are three types, each with a distinct purpose. Hyaline cartilage is the most widespread type. Fine type two collagen fibres give it a smooth, glassy appearance. You find it on articular surfaces, costal cartilages, the nasal septum, the larynx, and the tracheal rings. It offers a low-friction surface for movement. Fibrocartilage is the heavy-duty type. Thick bundles of type one collagen make it tough and opaque. It lacks a perichondrium. It appears where mechanical loads are highest: intervertebral discs, the pubic symphysis, the knee menisci, and the labrum. Elastic cartilage is the spring-back type. Elastin fibres make it flexible and slightly yellow. It returns to its original shape after bending. You find it in the pinna of the ear, the epiglottis, and the auditory tube. Think of hyaline as the default cartilage, fibrocartilage as the heavy-duty version, and elastic cartilage as the spring-back type.

8
00:09:30.975 --> 00:10:59.450
A joint, also called an articulation, is any place where two or more bones connect. Joints are classified structurally by the tissue that holds them together. Fibrous joints connect bones through fibrous connective tissue, with no joint cavity. Sutures between skull bones, like the coronal and sagittal sutures, are immovable in adults. The distal tibiofibular joint is a syndesmosis, held by an interosseous membrane and slightly movable. A gomphosis, the peg-in-socket joint, anchors each tooth in its alveolar socket via the periodontal ligament. Cartilaginous joints also lack a joint cavity. Primary types, called synchondroses, use hyaline cartilage and are temporary, converting to bone at maturity. Epiphyseal plates are a familiar example. Secondary types, called symphyses, use fibrocartilage and allow slight movement. The pubic symphysis and intervertebral discs are typical examples. Synovial joints are the most common type, especially in the limbs. They have a joint cavity filled with synovial fluid and allow free movement. Articular hyaline cartilage covers the bone ends, providing a smooth, low-friction surface. The articular capsule has a fibrous outer layer and an inner synovial membrane, which produces the synovial fluid. Ligaments reinforce the capsule and limit excessive movement. Some joints also contain accessory structures. These include intra-articular discs called menisci, a labrum, and fluid-filled sacs called bursae.

9
00:10:59.450 --> 00:12:23.175
Synovial joints are classified by the shape of their articular surfaces. That shape determines what movements are possible. The plane joint has flat surfaces, as seen in the acromioclavicular and intercarpal joints. The hinge joint permits flexion and extension only. A convex surface fits a concave one along a single axis. The elbow, ankle, and finger joints are hinge joints. The pivot joint allows rotation only, with one bone turning inside a bony ring. The atlantoaxial joint, between the first and second cervical vertebrae, is the classic example. The condyloid joint has an oval head in an oval socket, allowing flexion, extension, abduction, and adduction. Combining all four produces circumduction. The wrist and knuckle joints are condyloid. The saddle joint permits all movements except axial rotation. The only true saddle joint is at the base of the thumb. It gives humans their precision grip. The ball-and-socket joint allows full movement in every direction, including rotation. The shoulder and hip are the two examples. The key movements at synovial joints are flexion and extension, abduction and adduction, rotation, and circumduction. Special movements include pronation and supination at the forearm, and inversion and eversion at the foot. When examining a joint, follow the sequence: look, feel, then move. You will practise this in your clinical postings.

10
00:12:23.175 --> 00:13:38.875
In 1863, the British surgeon John Hilton described a pattern that still appears in every anatomy textbook. His law says that one nerve trunk serves three targets. First, it supplies the muscles that move a joint. Second, it supplies the skin over those muscles' insertions. Third, it supplies the interior of the joint itself. This matters because pain from a diseased joint travels along that shared nerve pathway. It can appear somewhere else entirely. That is called referred pain, and Hilton's law predicts exactly where it will land. Take the hip as an example. The hip joint is supplied by the obturator nerve and the femoral nerve. The obturator nerve also supplies the adductor muscles of the thigh. It also supplies the skin over the medial knee, the inner side of the knee. So when the hip is inflamed, pain travels along the obturator nerve pathway and reaches the knee instead. This occurs in conditions such as Perthes disease and severe osteoarthritis. This is why unexplained knee pain in a child always prompts an X-ray of the hip. The same logic applies to the shoulder. The axillary nerve supplies the glenohumeral joint, the deltoid muscle, and the skin over the deltoid. Shoulder pathology therefore produces pain in the outer arm.
